    <header>
        <h1>Hurricane Preparedness Guide</h1>
    </header>

    <div class="container">

        <div class="alert">
            <strong>Alert:</strong> Hurricanes can cause devastating damage to life and property. Make sure you’re prepared with the following guidelines.
        </div>

        <div class="content">
            <h2>Before a Hurricane: Preparation Steps</h2>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Create a Family Emergency Plan:</strong> Ensure every family member knows the plan for communication and evacuation.</li>
                <li><strong>Build an Emergency Kit:</strong> Prepare a kit with water, non-perishable food, medications, and other essentials (see checklist below).</li>
                <li><strong>Know Your Evacuation Route:</strong> Familiarize yourself with local evacuation routes and have an alternative plan if needed.</li>
                <li><strong>Protect Your Home:</strong> Install storm shutters or board up windows and doors. Secure outdoor furniture and remove debris that could become flying hazards.</li>
                <li><strong>Stay Informed:</strong> Monitor local news and weather alerts to stay updated on storm developments.</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

        <div class="content">
            <h2>During a Hurricane: Stay Safe</h2>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Stay Indoors:</strong> Remain in a secure room on the lowest floor of your home, away from windows and doors.</li>
                <li><strong>Avoid Flood Waters:</strong> Do not attempt to walk, drive, or swim through flood waters. Even a few inches of water can be deadly.</li>
                <li><strong>Use a Battery-Powered Radio:</strong> If power is lost, use a battery-powered radio to receive emergency information and instructions.</li>
                <li><strong>Follow Evacuation Orders:</strong> If you are ordered to evacuate, do so immediately. Do not wait for the hurricane to arrive before leaving.</li>
                <li><strong>Turn Off Utilities:</strong> If instructed, shut off gas, electricity, and water before the storm hits.</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

        <div class="content">
            <h2>After a Hurricane: Safety Tips</h2>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Wait for the All-Clear:</strong> Do not leave your safe area until authorities confirm that it’s safe to do so.</li>
                <li><strong>Inspect for Damage:</strong> Check your home for structural damage, gas leaks, and water line breaks. If your home is unsafe, evacuate immediately.</li>
                <li><strong>Avoid Downed Power Lines:</strong> Stay clear of any downed power lines and report them to local authorities.</li>
                <li><strong>Be Cautious of Flood Waters:</strong> Flood waters can contain dangerous debris, chemicals, and wildlife. Avoid them if possible.</li>
                <li><strong>Use Caution When Re-entering Your Home:</strong> Look for any signs of structural damage or hazards before going inside.</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

        <div class="content">
            <h2>Emergency Kit Checklist</h2>
            <ul>
                <li>Water (1 gallon per person per day for at least 3 days)</li>
                <li>Non-perishable food (3-day supply per person)</li>
                <li>Battery-powered or hand-crank radio</li>
                <li>Flashlight and extra batteries</li>
                <li>First aid kit and necessary medications</li>
                <li>Important documents (ID, insurance policies, etc.) in a waterproof container</li>
                <li>Extra cash (ATMs may not work during power outages)</li>
                <li>Charged mobile phone with portable charger</li>
            </ul>
            <a href="#" class="btn">Download Emergency Kit Checklist</a>
            <a href="#" class="btn">Find Nearest Shelter</a>
        </div>

